const faqSchema={"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "How much can I deduct for a conservation easement donation?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Conservation easement tax deduction amounts equal the difference between your property's fair market value before granting the easement (assuming highest and best use including development potential) and the value immediately after granting the easement (restricted to permitted uses). A qualified appraiser determines both values. For example, if your property is worth $3 million with development rights but only $1 million restricted to agricultural use, your deductible conservation contribution is $2 million. You can deduct up to 50% of your adjusted gross income annually (or 100% for qualifying farmers/ranchers) with unused amounts carried forward for up to 15 additional years. The total deduction over time equals the appraised easement value, subject to basis limitations and other IRS restrictions."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can I still live on my property after granting a conservation easement?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, conservation easements typically allow you to continue residing on your property, often permitting limited additional residential construction within defined building envelopes. Most easements allow maintaining and replacing existing homes, building one or two additional residences in designated areas, and normal residential uses like gardens, outbuildings, and driveways. What you cannot do is subdivide the property into residential lots, build extensive development, or engage in commercial activities inconsistent with conservation purposes. The specific rights you retain depend on easement terms negotiated with the holder. Many landowners continue living on and actively managing their land exactly as before the easement, with the primary difference being prohibition of future subdivision or development beyond what the easement permits."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What happens to a conservation easement when I die?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Conservation easements run with the land in perpetuity, binding all future owners including your heirs. When you die, heirs inherit the property still subject to all easement restrictions and obligations. The easement continues enforcing the same limitations on development and use. For estate tax purposes, the property is valued at its restricted-use value (post-easement value), not its development potential, reducing estate tax exposure. Heirs cannot modify or remove easement restrictions. They must continue complying with easement terms and cooperating with the holder organization's annual monitoring. Many families view this permanence positively since it prevents heirs from selling to developers and ensures the property remains intact across generations. However, heirs need to understand their responsibilities and the property's limitations before inheriting encumbered land."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Are there risks or downsides to conservation easements?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The primary downside is permanent loss of flexibility. You and all future owners forfeit the right to develop, subdivide, or substantially alter the property beyond permitted uses. If circumstances change\u2014family needs, economic opportunities, or personal preferences\u2014you cannot undo the easement. Property value decreases since development rights are gone, potentially making the property harder to sell. Some buyers avoid encumbered properties due to restrictions. Ongoing compliance obligations require cooperating with holder monitoring, maintaining conservation values, and potentially investing in land stewardship. If you or heirs violate easement terms, holders can sue for enforcement. For landowners genuinely committed to conservation, these \"downsides\" often align with their goals. However, anyone uncertain about permanent restrictions should not grant easements regardless of tax benefits."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can the IRS challenge my conservation easement tax deduction?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, the IRS frequently audits conservation easement deductions, particularly large ones exceeding $1 million. Common challenges include disputes over appraisal values, questions about conservation purpose legitimacy, technical compliance issues with easement terms or documentation, and concerns about inflated values. To minimize audit risk and defend challenges successfully, work with experienced professionals, obtain conservative appraisals from qualified appraisers, ensure genuine conservation purposes beyond tax motivation, document everything thoroughly, and file complete accurate tax forms. The IRS has shut down abusive conservation easement tax shelters but continues supporting legitimate conservation through proper easement structures. If you follow IRS guidelines, work with reputable land trusts, and avoid aggressive valuations, your conservation easement deduction should withstand scrutiny even if audited."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Do conservation easements work for small properties or just large ranches?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "While large properties most commonly use conservation easements, smaller parcels can qualify if they serve legitimate conservation purposes. Properties as small as 10-20 acres might qualify for conservation easement deductions if they protect important habitats, fill gaps in larger conservation areas, preserve scenic vistas, or protect historically significant structures. Small properties in or adjacent to urban areas might serve open space preservation purposes. However, transaction costs for conservation easements run $30,000-$100,000+ regardless of property size, so the tax benefits must exceed these costs significantly to make economic sense. For very small properties with modest easement values, transaction costs might consume too much of the tax benefit. Calculate whether your property's likely easement value (determined by preliminary discussions with appraisers and land trusts) justifies the professional costs required."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can I grant a conservation easement and later sell my property?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, you can sell property encumbered by conservation easement at any time. The easement remains in place binding the new owner to all restrictions and obligations. Selling doesn't affect the easement or your tax benefits already claimed. However, the property's market value will be its restricted-use value since development rights are gone. This typically means lower sale prices compared to what unencumbered property would sell for. Some buyers specifically seek conservation-protected land precisely because it cannot be developed. These conservation-minded buyers might pay premiums recognizing the permanent conservation protection. Other buyers avoid encumbered property due to restrictions. Marketing encumbered properties requires targeting the right buyer pool. The easement doesn't prevent sale, but it does affect who will buy and how much they'll pay."}}]};
